  "output": "## Test coverage analysis â€” jobsquare\n\n**Current state: zero tests.** No `tests/` directory, no `pytest.ini`/`pyproject.toml` test config, no test dependencies in `requirements.txt` (only `httpx`, `PyYAML`). 1,932 lines of Python across 8 modules, 100% untested. `fetchers.py` even documents itself as designed for testability (\"The HTTP client is injectable so the parsing logic is unit-testable against mocked transports without touching the network\") â€” that design intent was never followed up.\n\nI'd recommend adding `pytest`, `pytest-asyncio`, and `respx` (httpx-native mocking) to a new `requirements-dev.txt` before writing any of the skeletons below.\n\n---\n\n### Priority ranking (highest risk first)\n\n1. **`store.py`** â€” dedup is the whole point of the app; a bug here means silent data loss or duplicate spam. No tests at all, including no test of the SQLite schema/migration path.\n2. **`models.py`** â€” `parse_posted_at` handles 3 incompatible timestamp formats from different ATSes; `content_hash`/`key` drive dedup correctness in `store.py`.\n3. **`fetchers.py`** â€” largest surface, one parser per ATS, lots of defensive `.get()` chains that silently swallow malformed data instead of failing loudly. Parsers are pure functions and trivially testable but have zero coverage.\n4. **`filters.py`** â€” small but is the only thing standing between \"fetched 3000 jobs\" and \"user sees the 5 relevant ones.\" Regex-based include/exclude has boundary bugs waiting (word-boundary edge cases, empty rules).\n5. **`notify.py`** â€” env-var-gated dispatch with a bare `except Exception` in `dispatch` that will hide real bugs if untested.\n6. **`pipeline.py` / `agent.py` / `cli.py`** â€” orchestration/integration layer; needs fewer but higher-value tests (mostly integration-style).\n\n---\n\n### `models.py`\n\n**Untested:** `parse_posted_at`, `Job.key`, `Job.posted_dt`, `Job.content_hash`, `Job.to_row`.\n\n**Gaps / edge cases:**\n- Lever ms-epoch vs. second-epoch disambiguation (`>= 1e12` heuristic) â€” never verified against real boundary values.\n- Negative/garbage numeric strings (`\"-1\"`, `\"abc123\"` which `isdigit()` on `lstrip(\"-\")` would reject correctly, but no test proves it).\n- ISO strings with trailing `Z`, naive ISO strings (no tzinfo), and already-aware ISO strings â€” three different code paths in one function, no test distinguishes them.\n- Empty string / `None` input â†’ `None`.\n- Unparseable Workday prose (`\"Posted 3 Days Ago\"`) â†’ `None`, silently kept elsewhere (that's a cross-module interaction with `filters.py` worth an integration test too).\n- `content_hash` stability: same title/location/url/department â†’ same hash; changing any one of the four â†’ different hash; `raw` and `posted_at` must NOT affect the hash (that's the whole point â€” untested invariant).\n- `to_row()` must not include `raw` but must include computed `key`/`content_hash`.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_models.py\nimport pytest\nfrom datetime import timezone\nfrom models import Job, parse_posted_at\n\n\nclass TestParsePostedAt:\n    def test_empty_and_none(self):\n        assert parse_posted_at(\"\") is None\n        assert parse_posted_at(None) is None\n\n    def test_lever_millisecond_epoch(self):\n        dt = parse_posted_at(\"1643241332430\")\n        assert dt.tzinfo is timezone.utc\n        assert dt.year == 2022\n\n    def test_second_epoch_boundary(self):\n        # just under the 1e12 threshold -> treated as seconds\n        dt = parse_posted_at(\"999999999999\")\n        assert dt is not None\n\n    def test_iso_with_trailing_z(self):\n        dt = parse_posted_at(\"2024-01-15T10:00:00Z\")\n        assert dt.tzinfo == timezone.utc\n\n    def test_iso_naive_gets_utc(self):\n        dt = parse_posted_at(\"2024-01-15T10:00:00\")\n        assert dt.tzinfo == timezone.utc\n\n    def test_unparseable_prose_returns_none(self):\n        assert parse_posted_at(\"Posted 3 Days Ago\") is None\n\n    @pytest.mark.parametrize(\"bad\", [\"not-a-date\", \"12/32/2024\", \"   \"])\n    def test_garbage_returns_none(self, bad):\n        assert parse_posted_at(bad) is None\n\n\nclass TestJob:\n    def _job(self, **kw):\n        base = dict(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\",\n                    title=\"Engineer\", url=\"https://x/1\")\n        base.update(kw)\n        return Job(**base)\n\n    def test_key_is_stable_and_composite(self):\n        j = self._job()\n        assert j.key == \"greenhouse:acme:1\"\n\n    def test_content_hash_changes_with_title(self):\n        a, b = self._job(title=\"Engineer I\"), self._job(title=\"Engineer II\")\n        assert a.content_hash != b.content_hash\n\n    def test_content_hash_ignores_raw_and_posted_at(self):\n        a = self._job(raw={\"x\": 1}, posted_at=\"2024-01-01\")\n        b = self._job(raw={\"x\": 2}, posted_at=\"2025-06-01\")\n        assert a.content_hash == b.content_hash\n\n    def test_to_row_excludes_raw_includes_computed_fields(self):\n        row = self._job(raw={\"secret\": True}).to_row()\n        assert \"raw\" not in row\n        assert \"key\" in row and \"content_hash\" in row\n\n    def test_posted_dt_none_when_unparseable(self):\n        assert self._job(posted_at=\"garbage\").posted_dt is None\n```\n\n---\n\n### `filters.py`\n\n**Untested:** `match`, `filter_jobs`, `_compile`.\n\n**Gaps:**\n- Word-boundary regex on non-alphanumeric keywords (e.g. `\"C++\"`, `\"3D\"`) â€” `\\b` behaves oddly around punctuation; untested.\n- Empty `include`/`exclude`/`locations` lists vs. `None` â€” code does `if exclude:` so `[]` and `None` should behave identically, but nothing proves it.\n- Exclude takes priority over include when both match the same haystack.\n- Case-insensitivity of keyword matching and location substring matching.\n- `cutoff` behavior: job with unparseable `posted_at` must be **kept** even when a cutoff is set (explicit design comment) â€” this is the highest-value untested edge case in the file.\n- `max_age_days` as a float string (`\"3.5\"`) in `filter_jobs`.\n- Location substring match is bidirectional-looking but actually only checks `rule in job.location`, not the reverse â€” worth locking in with a test since it's easy to accidentally \"fix\" backwards later.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_filters.py\nfrom datetime import datetime, timedelta, timezone\nfrom models import Job\nfrom filters import match, filter_jobs\n\n\ndef _job(**kw):\n    base = dict(source=\"x\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Backend Engineer\",\n                url=\"u\", location=\"Seattle, WA\", department=\"Engineering\")\n    base.update(kw)\n    return Job(**base)\n\n\nclass TestMatch:\n    def test_exclude_overrides_include(self):\n        j = _job(title=\"Senior Backend Engineer (Contract)\")\n        assert not match(j, include=[\"engineer\"], exclude=[\"contract\"])\n\n    def test_include_case_insensitive(self):\n        assert match(_job(title=\"ENGINEER\"), include=[\"engineer\"])\n\n    def test_empty_lists_behave_like_none(self):\n        j = _job()\n        assert match(j, include=[], exclude=[], locations=[]) == match(j)\n\n    def test_word_boundary_avoids_partial_match(self):\n        # \"eng\" should not match \"Engineering\" as a substring keyword\n        j = _job(department=\"Engineering\")\n        assert not match(j, include=[\"eng \"])  # trailing space breaks \\b intentionally\n\n    def test_location_substring_case_insensitive(self):\n        assert match(_job(location=\"Seattle, WA\"), locations=[\"seattle\"])\n\n    def test_cutoff_drops_old_dated_job(self):\n        old = _job(posted_at=(datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=30)).isoformat())\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=7)\n        assert not match(old, cutoff=cutoff)\n\n    def test_cutoff_keeps_undated_job(self):\n        undated = _job(posted_at=\"\")\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=7)\n        assert match(undated, cutoff=cutoff)\n\n    def test_cutoff_keeps_unparseable_posted_at(self):\n        j = _job(posted_at=\"Posted 3 Days Ago\")\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=1)\n        assert match(j, cutoff=cutoff)\n\n\nclass TestFilterJobs:\n    def test_max_age_days_as_string(self):\n        old = _job(posted_at=(datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=10)).isoformat())\n        fresh = _job(external_id=\"2\",\n                     posted_at=datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat())\n        result = filter_jobs([old, fresh], {\"max_age_days\": \"3\"})\n        assert result == [fresh]\n\n    def test_no_rules_returns_all(self):\n        jobs = [_job(external_id=str(i)) for i in range(3)]\n        assert filter_jobs(jobs, {}) == jobs\n```\n\n---\n\n### `store.py`\n\n**Untested:** everything â€” `Store.__init__`/`_migrate`, `diff`, `_insert`/`_update`, `get_meta`/`set_meta`, `next_seq`, `added_since`, `count`, context-manager protocol.\n\n**Gaps (the highest-risk file in the repo):**\n- `diff()` three-way branch: brand-new key â†’ `new`; existing key with changed `content_hash` â†’ `changed` + `last_seen` bump; existing key with same hash â†’ neither, just `last_seen` bump. No test currently distinguishes these three outcomes.\n- Migration path: opening a pre-existing DB file that lacks `salary_range` should get the column added without data loss (`_migrate`). Nothing simulates an \"old\" schema.\n- `next_seq` concurrency claim (`BEGIN IMMEDIATE` for atomic increment) â€” this is explicitly called out as protecting against races between \"parallel pipeline workers\" (matches your memory note on parallel worker collisions), but there is no test exercising two callers racing on the same key.\n- `added_since` ordering guarantee (`ORDER BY first_seen, company, title`) and the strict `>` boundary (a row with `first_seen == ts` must be excluded).\n- `get_meta` returns `None` for a missing key vs. `set_meta` upsert (`ON CONFLICT... DO UPDATE`) â€” insert-then-update-same-key path untested.\n- Using `Store` as a context manager (`__enter__`/`__exit__`) closes the connection â€” untested that a second use after close raises rather than silently no-op.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_store.py\nimport pytest\nfrom store import Store\nfrom models import Job\n\n\n@pytest.fixture\ndef store(tmp_path):\n    with Store(tmp_path / \"test.db\") as s:\n        yield s\n\n\ndef _job(ext_id=\"1\", title=\"Engineer\"):\n    return Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=ext_id,\n               title=title, url=\"https://x\", location=\"Remote\")\n\n\nclass TestDiff:\n    def test_first_seen_job_is_new(self, store):\n        new, changed = store.diff([_job()])\n        assert len(new) == 1 and changed == []\n\n    def test_unchanged_job_is_neither(self, store):\n        store.diff([_job()])\n        new, changed = store.diff([_job()])\n        assert new == [] and changed == []\n\n    def test_changed_title_reports_as_changed(self, store):\n        store.diff([_job(title=\"Engineer I\")])\n        new, changed = store.diff([_job(title=\"Engineer II\")])\n        assert new == [] and len(changed) == 1\n\n    def test_last_seen_bumped_on_unchanged_reseen(self, store):\n        store.diff([_job()])\n        row_before = store.conn.execute(\n            \"SELECT last_seen FROM jobs WHERE key=?\", (_job().key,)).fetchone()\n        store.diff([_job()])\n        row_after = store.conn.execute(\n            \"SELECT last_seen FROM jobs WHERE key=?\", (_job().key,)).fetchone()\n        assert row_after[\"last_seen\"] >= row_before[\"last_seen\"]\n\n\nclass TestMigration:\n    def test_adds_salary_range_column_to_old_schema(self, tmp_path):\n        import sqlite3\n        path = tmp_path / \"old.db\"\n        conn = sqlite3.connect(path)\n        conn.executescript(\"\"\"\n            CREATE TABLE jobs (key TEXT PRIMARY KEY, source TEXT, company TEXT,\n                external_id TEXT, title TEXT, url TEXT, location TEXT,\n                department TEXT, employment_type TEXT, posted_at TEXT,\n                content_hash TEXT, first_seen TEXT, last_seen TEXT);\n        \"\"\")\n        conn.commit(); conn.close()\n        with Store(path) as s:\n            cols = {r[\"name\"] for r in s.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA table_info(jobs)\")}\n            assert \"salary_range\" in cols\n\n\nclass TestMeta:\n    def test_get_meta_missing_key_returns_none(self, store):\n        assert store.get_meta(\"nope\") is None\n\n    def test_set_then_get_roundtrip(self, store):\n        store.set_meta(\"k\", \"v1\")\n        assert store.get_meta(\"k\") == \"v1\"\n\n    def test_set_meta_upserts(self, store):\n        store.set_meta(\"k\", \"v1\")\n        store.set_meta(\"k\", \"v2\")\n        assert store.get_meta(\"k\") == \"v2\"\n\n    def test_next_seq_increments(self, store):\n        assert store.next_seq(\"counter\") == 1\n        assert store.next_seq(\"counter\") == 2\n\n\nclass TestAddedSince:\n    def test_excludes_exact_boundary_timestamp(self, store):\n        store.diff([_job()])\n        ts = store.conn.execute(\"SELECT first_seen FROM jobs\").fetchone()[0]\n        assert store.added_since(ts) == []\n\n    def test_orders_by_first_seen_company_title(self, store):\n        store.diff([_job(\"1\", \"Zebra\"), _job(\"2\", \"Apple\")])\n        rows = store.added_since(\"1970-01-01T00:00:00+00:00\")\n        titles = [r[\"title\"] for r in rows]\n        assert titles == sorted(titles)\n```\n\n---\n\n### `fetchers.py`\n\n**Untested:** every `parse_*` function (14+ ATS parsers), `_request` retry/backoff logic, `_balanced_json`, `fetch_all` concurrency/error-isolation, `fetch_source` dispatch, and every bespoke `fetch_*` (ashby fallback, google pagination, meta doc_id/token scraping, apple hydration parsing, deshaw/twosigma HTML scraping, bytedance strict-schema POST).\n\nThis is where most of the *business logic* actually lives, and it's the largest blind spot. Since parsers are pure functions, they're cheap to test with fixture payloads.\n\n**Gaps:**\n- Each `parse_*` needs at least: (a) a normal full payload â†’ correct `Job` fields, (b) missing/`None` optional fields don't crash (`(j.get(\"location\") or {}).get(...)` chains), (c) empty list/dict input â†’ `[]`.\n- `_lever_salary`/`_ashby_salary`/`_amazon_posted_at` â€” small pure helpers with several branches, currently 0% covered.\n- `_balanced_json`: nested braces, braces inside quoted strings, escaped quotes, unterminated input â†’ `None`.\n- `_request`: retries on 429/500/502/503/504, does **not** retry on 4xx (e.g. 404), exhausts retries and raises `RuntimeError`, honors `retries` count. This needs a mocked transport (`httpx.MockTransport`) â€” currently the retry/backoff path has never executed under test.\n- `fetch_all`: one source raising should not abort the others (`except Exception` in `one()`); result ordering/flattening across sources.\n- `_apple_hydration` / `_extract_ds1` (Google): regex-based extraction from HTML blobs â€” brittle by nature (comment literally warns \"field indices are positional and undocumented\"), yet has zero regression tests pinning current expected behavior against a fixture HTML snippet. This is exactly the kind of code that silently breaks on a site redesign and a fixture-based test is the cheapest insurance available.\n- `fetch_ashby`: 200 path vs. 404-fallback-to-HTML path vs. other status code â†’ `raise_for_status()`.\n- `parse_meta`/`parse_google`/`parse_amazon` dedup-by-`external_id` behavior across pages.\n- Amazon `_amazon_posted_at` malformed date string â†’ `\"\"` (not a crash).\n\n```python\n# tests/test_fetchers_parsers.py\nimport pytest\nfrom fetchers import (parse_greenhouse, parse_lever, _lever_salary, parse_ashby,\n                       _amazon_posted_at, parse_amazon, _balanced_json)\n\n\nclass TestParseGreenhouse:\n    def test_maps_core_fields(self):\n        data = {\"jobs\": [{\"id\": 1, \"title\": \"SWE\", \"absolute_url\": \"u\",\n                          \"location\": {\"name\": \"NYC\"},\n                          \"departments\": [{\"name\": \"Eng\"}],\n                          \"updated_at\": \"2024-01-01\"}]}\n        [job] = parse_greenhouse(\"acme\", data)\n        assert job.external_id == \"1\" and job.location == \"NYC\"\n        assert job.department == \"Eng\"\n\n    def test_empty_jobs_list(self):\n        assert parse_greenhouse(\"acme\", {\"jobs\": []}) == []\n\n    def test_missing_optional_fields_do_not_crash(self):\n        [job] = parse_greenhouse(\"acme\", {\"jobs\": [{\"id\": 2}]})\n        assert job.title == \"\" and job.location == \"\"\n\n\nclass TestLeverSalary:\n    def test_range_present(self):\n        j = {\"salaryRange\": {\"min\": 100000, \"max\": 150000, \"currency\": \"USD\"}}\n        assert _lever_salary(j) == \"USD 100,000â€“150,000\"\n\n    def test_falls_back_to_description(self):\n        j = {\"salaryDescriptionPlain\": \"Competitive\"}\n        assert _lever_salary(j) == \"Competitive\"\n\n    def test_no_salary_data_returns_empty(self):\n        assert _lever_salary({}) == \"\"\n\n\nclass TestParseAshby:\n    def test_skips_unlisted_jobs(self):\n        data = {\"jobs\": [{\"id\": \"1\", \"isListed\": False}, {\"id\": \"2\", \"title\": \"T\"}]}\n        result = parse_ashby(\"acme\", data)\n        assert len(result) == 1 and result[0].external_id == \"2\"\n\n\nclass TestAmazonPostedAt:\n    def test_valid_date(self):\n        assert _amazon_posted_at(\"June 26, 2026\") == \"2026-06-26T00:00:00+00:00\"\n\n    def test_malformed_returns_empty(self):\n        assert _amazon_posted_at(\"not a date\") == \"\"\n\n    def test_empty_string(self):\n        assert _amazon_posted_at(\"\") == \"\"\n\n\nclass TestBalancedJson:\n    def test_simple_object(self):\n        assert _balanced_json('{\"a\": 1}', 0) == '{\"a\": 1}'\n\n    def test_nested_braces(self):\n        text = '{\"a\": {\"b\": 1}}'\n        assert _balanced_json(text, 0) == text\n\n    def test_brace_inside_string_is_ignored(self):\n        text = '{\"a\": \"}\"}'\n        assert _balanced_json(text, 0) == text\n\n    def test_escaped_quote_inside_string(self):\n        text = r'{\"a\": \"\\\"\"}'\n        assert _balanced_json(text, 0) == text\n\n    def test_unterminated_returns_none(self):\n        assert _balanced_json('{\"a\": 1', 0) is None\n```\n\n```python\n# tests/test_fetchers_http.py â€” needs respx (pip install respx)\nimport httpx\nimport pytest\nimport respx\nfrom fetchers import _request, fetch_all\n\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nclass TestRequestRetries:\n    async def test_retries_on_503_then_succeeds(self, respx_mock):\n        route = respx_mock.get(\"https://x/y\").mock(\n            side_effect=[httpx.Response(503), httpx.Response(200, json={})])\n        async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n            r = await _request(client, \"https://x/y\", retries=3)\n        assert r.status_code == 200\n        assert route.call_count == 2\n\n    async def test_does_not_retry_on_404(self, respx_mock):\n        respx_mock.get(\"https://x/y\").mock(return_value=httpx.Response(404))\n        async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n            with pytest.raises(RuntimeError):\n                await _request(client, \"https://x/y\", retries=3)\n        assert respx_mock.calls.call_count == 1\n\n    async def test_exhausts_retries_and_raises(self, respx_mock):\n        respx_mock.get(\"https://x/y\").mock(return_value=httpx.Response(500))\n        async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n            with pytest.raises(RuntimeError):\n                await _request(client, \"https://x/y\", retries=2)\n\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nclass TestFetchAll:\n    async def test_one_source_failure_does_not_abort_others(self, respx_mock):\n        respx_mock.get(\"https://boards-api.greenhouse.io/v1/boards/bad/jobs\").mock(\n            return_value=httpx.Response(500))\n        respx_mock.get(\"https://boards-api.greenhouse.io/v1/boards/good/jobs\").mock(\n            return_value=httpx.Response(200, json={\"jobs\": [{\"id\": 1, \"title\": \"T\"}]}))\n        sources = [{\"ats\": \"greenhouse\", \"company\": \"bad\"},\n                   {\"ats\": \"greenhouse\", \"company\": \"good\"}]\n        jobs = await fetch_all(sources, concurrency=2)\n        assert len(jobs) == 1\n```\n\n---\n\n### `notify.py`\n\n**Untested:** all five notifiers, `_line`, `_sms_body`, `dispatch`.\n\n**Gaps:**\n- Every notifier's env-var gate: `notify_slack`/`notify_webhook`/`notify_email`/`notify_sms` must no-op both when the relevant env var is unset **and** when there's nothing to report â€” two independent short-circuit conditions, easy to accidentally collapse into one and lose a case.\n- `dispatch`'s bare `except Exception` swallowing a notifier failure and continuing to the next one â€” untested that a Slack failure doesn't block console/email/SMS.\n- `_sms_body` truncation at `limit` (default 8) and the `\"+N more\"` suffix â€” boundary at exactly `limit` vs. `limit+1`.\n- `notify_sms` requires **all four** Twilio env vars; missing any one should no-op (not partially send).\n- `httpx.post` calls should be mocked, not hit real endpoints â€” `notify_slack`/`notify_webhook`/`notify_sms` currently untestable without `monkeypatch`/`respx`.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_notify.py\nimport httpx\nimport pytest\nimport respx\nfrom models import Job\nimport notify\n\n\ndef _job(title=\"Engineer\"):\n    return Job(source=\"x\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=title, url=\"u\")\n\n\nclass TestSlack:\n    def test_noop_without_webhook_url(self, monkeypatch):\n        monkeypatch.delenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", raising=False)\n        # should not raise even though it would otherwise try to POST\n        notify.notify_slack([_job()], [])\n\n    def test_noop_with_no_jobs(self, monkeypatch, respx_mock):\n        monkeypatch.setenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", \"https://hooks.slack.com/x\")\n        route = respx_mock.post(\"https://hooks.slack.com/x\")\n        notify.notify_slack([], [])\n        assert route.call_count == 0\n\n    def test_posts_when_configured_and_new_jobs(self, monkeypatch, respx_mock):\n        monkeypatch.setenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", \"https://hooks.slack.com/x\")\n        route = respx_mock.post(\"https://hooks.slack.com/x\").mock(\n            return_value=httpx.Response(200))\n        notify.notify_slack([_job()], [])\n        assert route.call_count == 1\n\n\nclass TestSmsBody:\n    def test_truncates_at_limit_with_more_suffix(self):\n        jobs = [_job(f\"T{i}\") for i in range(10)]\n        body = notify._sms_body(jobs, [], limit=8)\n        assert \"+2 more\" in body\n        assert body.count(\"\\n- \") == 8\n\n    def test_exactly_at_limit_no_suffix(self):\n        jobs = [_job(f\"T{i}\") for i in range(8)]\n        body = notify._sms_body(jobs, [], limit=8)\n        assert \"more\" not in body\n\n\nclass TestSmsGating:\n    def test_noop_if_any_twilio_var_missing(self, monkeypatch, respx_mock):\n        monkeypatch.setenv(\"TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID\", \"sid\")\n        monkeypatch.setenv(\"TWILIO_AUTH_TOKEN\", \"tok\")\n        monkeypatch.delenv(\"TWILIO_FROM\", raising=False)\n        monkeypatch.setenv(\"TWILIO_TO\", \"+1555\")\n        route = respx_mock.post(url__regex=r\".*twilio.*\")\n        notify.notify_sms([_job()], [])\n        assert route.call_count == 0\n\n\nclass TestDispatch:\n    def test_one_notifier_failure_does_not_block_others(self, monkeypatch, capsys):\n        calls = []\n        def boom(new, changed): raise RuntimeError(\"slack down\")\n        def ok(new, changed): calls.append(\"ok\")\n        monkeypatch.setattr(notify, \"NOTIFIERS\", [boom, ok])\n        notify.dispatch([_job()], [])\n        assert calls == [\"ok\"]\n        assert \"! notifier boom failed\" in capsys.readouterr().out\n```\n\n---\n\n### `pipeline.py` / `cli.py` â€” integration gaps\n\n**Untested:** `load_config` defaulting behavior, `run()` end-to-end (dry-run vs. persisting), `run_sync`, `cli.main` argument parsing.\n\n**Gaps:**\n- `load_config` defaults: missing `sources`/`filters`/`db`/`concurrency` keys should be filled in, not KeyError.\n- `run(dry_run=True)` must **not** touch the `Store` (no dedup state mutation) â€” currently only enforced by code reading, not a test.\n- `run()` non-dry-run path: full round trip fetchâ†’filterâ†’diffâ†’dispatch, using a monkeypatched `fetch_all` to avoid network, and a `tmp_path` sqlite db â€” this is the one true integration test the project is missing.\n- `cli.main`'s `--dry-run` flag actually threading through to `run_sync`.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_pipeline.py\nimport pytest\nfrom pipeline import load_config, run\nfrom models import Job\n\n\nclass TestLoadConfig:\n    def test_fills_in_defaults(self, tmp_path):\n        cfg_path = tmp_path / \"c.yaml\"\n        cfg_path.write_text(\"sources: []\\n\")\n        cfg = load_config(cfg_path)\n        assert cfg[\"filters\"] == {} and cfg[\"db\"] == \"jobs.db\"\n        assert cfg[\"concurrency\"] == 8\n\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nclass TestRun:\n    async def test_dry_run_does_not_persist(self, tmp_path, monkeypatch):\n        cfg_path = tmp_path / \"c.yaml\"\n        db_path = tmp_path / \"j.db\"\n        cfg_path.write_text(f\"sources: [{{ats: greenhouse, company: acme}}]\\ndb: {db_path}\\n\")\n\n        async def fake_fetch_all(sources, concurrency):\n            return [Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\",\n                        title=\"Engineer\", url=\"u\")]\n        monkeypatch.setattr(\"pipeline.fetch_all\", fake_fetch_all)\n\n        result = await run(cfg_path, dry_run=True)\n        assert result[\"new\"] == 0\n        assert not db_path.exists()\n\n    async def test_full_run_persists_new_jobs(self, tmp_path, monkeypatch):\n        cfg_path = tmp_path / \"c.yaml\"\n        db_path = tmp_path / \"j.db\"\n        cfg_path.write_text(f\"sources: [{{ats: greenhouse, company: acme}}]\\ndb: {db_path}\\n\")\n\n        async def fake_fetch_all(sources, concurrency):\n            return [Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\",\n                        title=\"Engineer\", url=\"u\")]\n        monkeypatch.setattr(\"pipeline.fetch_all\", fake_fetch_all)\n        monkeypatch.setattr(\"pipeline.dispatch\", lambda new, changed: None)\n\n        result = await run(cfg_path, dry_run=False)\n        assert result[\"new\"] == 1\n        assert db_path.exists()\n```\n\n---\n\n### `agent.py` â€” deterministic-helper gaps\n\n**Untested:** `cmd_db_new` (watermark/truncation/posted-days logic â€” the most intricate function in the file), `cmd_db_mark` (validates ISO timestamp, rejects garbage with exit code 2), `cmd_report_num`, `_normalize_ats` (ATS character replacement, skips `<style>`/`<script>`/tags), `_chrome_bin` discovery order. The `pdf-render` Chrome subprocess call and `run_claude`'s `os.execvp`/`subprocess.call` launcher are integration-only concerns â€” fine to leave for manual/smoke testing, but `cmd_db_new`'s group-boundary truncation logic and `_normalize_ats` are pure and cheap to test.\n\n**Gaps:**\n- `cmd_db_new`'s \"truncate only at `first_seen` group boundaries\" logic â€” the subtle invariant that a partial group is never split. Needs a test with two rows sharing one `first_seen` timestamp that together exceed `--limit`.\n- `--posted-days` + `--dated-only` interaction: undated rows kept vs. dropped are two different flags.\n- `cmd_db_mark` rejecting a non-ISO watermark string with exit code 2 and no DB mutation.\n- `_normalize_ats`: smart quotes/em-dash replaced in body text but **not** inside `<style>`/`<script>` blocks or tag attributes â€” this is exactly the kind of regex-based text/tag interleaving bug that regresses silently.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_agent_helpers.py\nimport json\nimport pytest\nfrom agent import cmd_db_new, cmd_db_mark, _normalize_ats\nfrom store import Store\nfrom models import Job\n\n\ndef _seed(db_path, rows):\n    with Store(db_path) as s:\n        for ts, jobs in rows:\n            # simulate first_seen by directly inserting with a fixed timestamp\n            for j in jobs:\n                s.diff([j])\n\n\nclass TestNormalizeAts:\n    def test_replaces_smart_quotes_in_body(self):\n        html = \"<p>\\u201Chello\\u201D</p>\"\n        out, counts = _normalize_ats(html)\n        assert '\"hello\"' in out\n        assert counts.get(\"smart-double-quote\") == 2\n\n    def test_does_not_touch_style_block(self):\n        html = \"<style>p::before{content:'\\u2014'}</style><p>\\u2014</p>\"\n        out, counts = _normalize_ats(html)\n        assert \"\\u2014\" in out.split(\"</style>\")[0]   # untouched inside style\n        assert \"-\" in out.split(\"</style>\")[1]         # replaced in body\n\n    def test_does_not_touch_tag_attributes(self):\n        html = '<a title=\"\\u2014\">x\\u2014y</a>'\n        out, _ = _normalize_ats(html)\n        assert 'title=\"\\u2014\"' in out       # attribute untouched\n        assert \"x-y\" in out                  # body text replaced\n\n\nclass TestDbMark:\n    def test_rejects_non_iso_watermark(self, tmp_path, capsys):\n        cfg = tmp_path / \"c.yaml\"\n        cfg.write_text(f\"db: {tmp_path / 'j.db'}\\n\")\n        rc = cmd_db_mark([\"not-a-timestamp\", \"-c\", str(cfg)])\n        assert rc == 2\n        assert \"not an ISO timestamp\" in capsys.readouterr().err\n```\n\n---\n\n### Summary of biggest structural gaps\n\n| Gap | Why it matters |\n|---|---|\n| No `store.py` tests at all | Correctness of dedup/diff is the core value proposition; a regression here means silent duplicate notifications or lost postings |\n| No HTTP-mocked tests for `_request` retry logic | Retry/backoff is the only thing standing between a transient 503 and a failed scrape; untested since inception |\n| No fixture-based tests for the scrape-fragile parsers (Google `ds:1`, Apple hydration, D.E. Shaw/Two Sigma HTML) | These are explicitly documented as brittle to site redesigns; 